title: Who will be elected governor of New Hampshire in 2020?
preds: Polls showing a strong lean Republican.
Only a few polls in the last several months have the Rep ahead by anything less than double digits. It's a formality at this point.

"In the races beyond Missouri, Montana, and North Carolina, the incumbent party should be able to retain their seat on Election Night. This includes two Republican incumbents in otherwise Democratic-leaning states: Chris Sununu in New Hampshire and Phil Scott in Vermont. Sununu and especially Scott have taken a more pragmatic approach than Trump, allowing them to win the support of ticket-splitters in their states." https://www.usnews.com/news/elections/articles/2020-10-29/analysis-republicans-maintain-edge-in-governor-races

"Sununu, a Republican, has won the governorship of the Granite State for two two-year terms, despite the GOP's weakened position in New England. The incumbent was already in a strong position for a third term thanks to generally well-received efforts to contain the coronavirus; the state’s late Democratic primary, on Sept. 8, has also helped to solidify his position. In the primary, state Senate Majority Leader Dan Feltes defeated executive councilor Andru Volinsky, 52%-48%. Feltes was the establishment candidate (Volinsky was popular on the party’s left) so he’s a credible general election challenger. But he’s largely unknown, and after spending heavily to win the primary, he now has little time in a cluttered political landscape to make an impression on voters. We’re moving this race from Lean Republican to Likely Republican." https://www.usnews.com/news/elections/articles/2020-10-13/analysis-republicans-look-poised-to-maintain-edge-in-governors-mansions
Incumbent Sununu holds leads of over 25% against Democratic challenger Feltes. Don't see gap closing any time soon.

From a Cook Political report update out today: "We are leaving GOP Gov. Chris Sununu in the Likely Republican column for now given that the primary was just last Tuesday, setting up a race with state Senate Majority Leader Dan Feltes. The newly-minted Democratic nominee doesn't have much time to gain momentum though, with a University of New Hampshire poll conducted just before the primary (Aug. 28-Sept. 1) found Sununu with a 24 point lead over Feltes. Another worrisome sign for Feltes is that Sununu also got 4,276 write-in votes in the Democratic primary or about 3% of all the primary votes." https://cookpolitical.com/analysis/governors/governors-overview/governors-updates-rating-changes-missouri-and-vermont
Gov Sununu currently leads by 20+ points over the Democratic nominee. He is widely seen as effectively managing the pandemic. Barring an unforeseen crisis, his lead seems safe.
Republicans all but guaranteed to keep this seat.

The Sunoco family are still sure-fire winners in New Hampshire. Assuming that the Pillsbury Doughboy's son wins the R primary, as he is certain to, he will be re-elected comfortably.  (This will have no effect on the presidential or Senate races there, both of which will go D--New Hampshirites are dedicated and accomplished ticket-splitters.)
Reviewing on polling over the last year.  Relatively consistent between 62 and 58 percent

Updating based on recent July 28th polling showing a 36.67 point average lead by the Republican incumbent. For the tide to turn it would take an event outside of traditional campaigning to occur in the next 90 days.

Sununu enjoyed a 77% approval rating in the most recent live telephone operator poll – conducted in mid-June by the Saint Anselm College Survey Center. Eighty-nine percent of Republicans, 79% of independents, and 62 percent of Democrats all gave him a thumbs up. And the governor’s favorable rating stood at 73 percent (https://www.concordmonitor.com/On-the-Trail-Steinhauser-35058546) Limited polling looks good for him too (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/governor/new-hampshire/)

I think Biden might beat trump in prez race, but sununu well known incumbent, and the state has an independent streak.  I suspect gop will keep governor position regardless of what happens in prez race
New Hampshire voters are champion ticket-splitters.  They will re-elect Sunoco the Younger and also go for Biden, both by comfortable margins.
